“We were worried before COVID-19 as a Black business owner,” Bartholomew said.
Black businesses were already in trouble before COVID-19.
The Small Business Administration said Black business owners are three times more likely to have trouble accessing capital — affecting their profitability — compared to white business owners.
Despite making up nearly a quarter of the city’s population, Black businesses in the Big Apple comprise just 2 percent of companies overall and less than 2 percent of city contracted businesses.
“We can’t all be horrible business people who are uneducated,” said Zevilla Jackson Preston, an architect and member of the Black Business Empowerment Committee, a coalition of business owners, community organizations and churches working to create and preserve Black businesses.